 of health care and science through nursing, physiotherapy and research are discussed, as is women's work, from domestic labour to dressmaking to broadcasting to banking. Using diary accounts, oral history, letters, organizational records, paintings, quilts, dressmaking patterns, milliners' records, posters, Framing our Past offers a unique opportunity to share what is rarely if ever seen, offering insights into the preservation and interpretation of historical sources.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aAinley, Marianne Gosztonyi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArnup, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaltessen, Jody, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBates, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourgeois, Isabelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBremault, Lise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamacchio, Cynthia R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCatton, J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCatton, R, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChurch, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aComacchio, Cynthia R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Sharon Anne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCook, Sharon Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCovert, Rosemary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrossfield, E. Tina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCr